  "local_port": 40576,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do you reduce the magnification of your screen?",
  "response": "To reduce the magnification of your screen, you can change the zoom settings on your computer or adjust the display settings. Here\u2019s how you can do it on different operating systems:\n\n### Windows:\n1. **Using Keyboard Shortcuts:**\n   - Press `Ctrl` and `-` (minus) key together to zoom out.\n   - You can also press `Ctrl` and `0` (zero) to reset the zoom to default.\n\n2. **Using Browser or Application Settings:**\n   - In most web browsers, you can click on the menu (three dots or lines) in the upper-right corner and use the zoom option to adjust the magnification.\n\n3. **Using Magnifier Tool (if you\u2019re using it):**\n   - Press `Windows` key + `Esc` to close the Magnifier or locate the Magnifier application and adjust the magnification level there.\n\n4. **Adjust Display Settings:**\n   - Right-click the desktop, select `Display settings`, and find the `Scale and layout` section. You can adjust the scale to make text and other items smaller or larger.\n\n### macOS:\n1. **Using Keyboard Shortcuts:**\n   - Press `Command` and `-` (minus) key together to zoom out.\n\n2. **Using System Preferences:**\n   - Go to `System Preferences`, then `Displays`. Here you can adjust the resolution or scaling options depending on your display settings.\n\n3. **Using Safari or Other Applications:**\n   - In Safari, go to `View` in the menu bar and select `Zoom Out`. Similar options exist in most applications.\n\n4. **Using Accessibility Features:**\n   - If you are using a zoom accessibility feature, you can go to `System Preferences`, `Accessibility`, then `Zoom` to adjust or disable these settings.\n\n### Chromebook:\n1. **Using Keyboard Shortcuts:**\n   - Press `Ctrl` and `-` (minus) key together to zoom out.\n\n2. **Using Settings:**\n   - Click on the clock in the bottom-right corner, select `Settings`, then `Device`, and choose `Displays`. Adjust the settings under `Display size`.\n\nIn most cases, using keyboard shortcuts is the quickest way to adjust magnification on your screen. If you find that the issue persists, it might be helpful to check if any zoom or accessibility features are turned on unintentionally.",
